<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10037d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10037d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10037d"> 37(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> vellum (veau) / parchment</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Un peu avant l&apos;&egrave;re chr&eacute;tienne, le <i>parchemin</i> vint faire concurrence au <i>papyrus</i>. Le parchemin ayant &eacute;t&eacute; tout d&apos;abord pr&eacute;par&eacute; &agrave; Pergame (Asie), on lui donna le nom g&eacute;n&eacute;rique de <i>pergamenum;</i> il &eacute;tait fait avec toutes sortes de peaux, mais le mouton a toujours &eacute;t&eacute; le plus commun; quant au veau, il re&ccedil;ut le nom sp&eacute;cial de <i>v&eacute;lin</i>. <font color="green">[Shortly before the Christian Era, parchment began to compete with papyrus. Parchment having first been made in Pergamum (Asia) was given the generic name pergamenum. It was made from all sorts of skins but sheepskin was always the most common. As for calf-skin, it was given the special name vellum.]</font> <small> Eug&egrave;ne Gallois, <a name="EGLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EGLP"><cite title="source">La Poste</cite></a> (1894) 48</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01015g" href="c01all.htm#c01015g">VI.C.01:015(g)</a>, <a name="c01015h" href="c01all.htm#c01015h">VI.C.01:015(h)</a> </mm></dd> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c01015d" href="c01all.htm#c01015d">VI.C.01:015(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
